Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read the Prime Minister’s statement for the latest information.

There are currently no commercial options to return to the UK from Lesotho. Medical evacuation flights remain possible.
Lesotho’s borders remain closed. Movement of persons in or out of Lesotho is prohibited, except for medical emergencies. SAA Airlink flights between Maseru and Johannesburg Airport have been suspended.
We know this is concerning for British people trying to leave Lesotho. The British High Commission is in contact with airlines and local authorities to ensure that British people can return to the UK from Lesotho as soon as possible.
Future options
If you are a British national currently visiting Lesotho and would like to return home to the UK, the British High Commission can update you when flight options become available by adding you to a mailing list. If you would like to receive these updates, email BHC.Maseru@fco.gov.uk with the subject heading ‘return from Lesotho’ and include your name, mobile telephone number, location and any other relevant information.
You should also Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British High Commission on @AnneMacroUK.
If you cannot leave Lesotho at this time, see advice on staying in Lesotho during coronavirus
Departing Lesotho via South Africa
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has advised that foreign visitors are permitted to leave Lesotho to catch flights out of South Africa if flights resume. However, visitors to Lesotho must travel through, or transit via, South Africa.
South Africa has put in place travel restrictions and visa requirements for individuals from countries affected by coronavirus (COVID-19), including the United Kingdom. If you are considering travelling to South Africa please refer to the FCO travel advice for South Africa for the latest information.
The South African High Commission Maseru is temporarily closed but may still issue visas in emergency situations.
Your journey home: re-entering the UK
When you return, you must follow the rules for entering the UK. You:
need to provide your journey and contact details up to 48 hours before you’re due to arrive in the UK
are not allowed to leave the place you’re staying for the first 14 days you’re in the UK except in very limited situations (known as ‘self-isolating’)
See also the list of people who are exempt from the border rules.
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) also provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
Help and support
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If departure options are available but you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, you should contact Corporate Travel Management (CTM). CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the British High Commission Pretoria, (which provides consular support to British nationals in Lesotho) on +27 12 421 7500
The High Commission cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available. To get the latest information, sign up for travel advice email alerts.
